  "prompt": "Why does Apple not put a Flashlight on the iPad?",
  "response": "Apple has not included a flashlight feature on the iPad for several reasons:\n\n1. **Design and Form Factor**: iPads are larger than iPhones and are typically used in different contexts. The form factor makes it less practical to use an iPad as a handheld flashlight.\n\n2. **User Scenario**: iPads are often used in stationary contexts, such as for work, browsing, or consumption of media. In contrast, iPhones are frequently carried around and used on the go, where a flashlight feature is more beneficial.\n\n3. **Alternative Solutions**: Users can utilize the screen brightness on an iPad to provide light if necessary, or they can use an external app that takes advantage of the camera flash accessories if available for certain iPad models.\n\n4. **Market Positioning**: Apple may also be focusing on distinguishing the iPhone as the device with features tailored for portability and everyday emergencies, while the iPad serves more as a versatile tablet for productivity and entertainment.\n\nWhile many users might appreciate a flashlight feature, it appears that Apple's design considerations have led them to prioritize other functionalities for the iPad instead.",
